{{about|the mathematician|the spammer|Laurence Canter and Martha Siegel}} '''Martha Jochnowitz Siegel''' is an American [[applied mathematics|applied mathematician]], [[probability theory|probability theorist]] and [[mathematics education|mathematics educator]] who served as the editor of ''[[Mathematics Magazine]]'' from 1991 to 1996.{{r|towson|centennial}} In 2017 she won the Yueh-Gin Gung and Dr. Charles Y. Hu Award for Distinguished Service of the [[Mathematical Association of America]] for "her remarkable leadership in guiding the national conversation on undergraduate mathematics curriculum".{{r|towson|gunghu}} She was a faculty member in the mathematics department of [[Towson University]] from 1971 until 2015, when she became a [[professor emerita]].{{r|towson}}
==Education and career== Siegel grew up in [[Brooklyn]], the daughter of civil engineer Nat Jochnowitz.{{r|gunghu}} She became interested in mathematics through her father's interest in mathematical puzzles,{{r|centennial}} and through the calculation of [[baseball statistics]] for the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]].{{r|gunghu}} She did her undergraduate studies in mathematics at [[Russell Sage College]], a small [[women's college]] in [[Troy, New York]], while also taking classes at the nearby men-only [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]],{{r|tiger}} as at that time Russell Sage had no mathematics department.{{r|centennial}} At Russell Sage, she was a Kellas honor student, and president of the science club.{{r|arrives}} She completed her Ph.D. in 1969 at the [[University of Rochester]]; her dissertation, ''On Birth and Death Processes'', was supervised by [[Johannes Kemperman]].{{r|tiger|mgp}} During graduate school and until her 1971 move to Towson, she was on the faculty at [[Goucher College]].{{r|tiger}}
==Contributions== At Towson, in 1981, Siegel founded an innovative and still-ongoing undergraduate applied mathematics program involving projects connected to local business and government. She is a co-author of the [[discrete mathematics]] and [[precalculus]] textbooks ''Finite Mathematics and Its Applications'' and ''Functioning in the Real World''. She also served as chair of a committee of the Mathematical Association of America charged with producing the 2015 edition of their ''MAA Curriculum Guide to Undergraduate Majors in the Mathematical Sciences''.{{r|gunghu}}
