{{Infobox legislation |short_title = Official Languages Ordinance |legislature = [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] |image = Hong Kong SAR Regional Emblem.svg |imagesize = |imagealt = |caption = |long_title = An Ordinance to provide for the official languages of Hong Kong, and for their status and use. |citation = {{Cite Hong Kong ordinance|5}} |territorial_extent = |enacted_by = [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] |date_enacted = |date_passed = |date_passed2 = |date_assented = |royal_assent = |date_signed = |date_commenced = 15 February 1974 |date_of_expiry = |date_repealed = |administered_by = |bill = |bill_citation = |bill_date = 11 January 1974 |introduced_by = [[Secretary for Home Affairs]] [[Denis Campbell Bray]] |1st_reading = 30 January 1974 |2nd_reading = 13 February 1974 |3rd_reading = 13 February 1974 |conf_committee_passed = |date_conf_committee = |white_paper = |committee_report = |amendments = 1975, 1980, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1992, 1994, 1995, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2011, 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=Enactment History of Cap. 5 Official Languages Ordinance|url=https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap5?tab=o|website=Cap. 5 Official Languages Ordinance|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> |repeals = |related_legislation = |summary = |keywords = |status = Current }} The '''Official Languages Ordinance''' is an ordinance of [[Hong Kong]] enacted for the purpose of specifying the status and use of [[official language]]s of the territory. Both [[Chinese languages|Chinese]] and [[English language|English]] are declared official languages with equal status in the ordinance, and are to be used in communication between the government and members of the public.<ref name="cap5_sec3">{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.hk/blis_ind.nsf/CurAllEngDoc/B6AC5FB0CF260FFDC825648000408D51?OpenDocument|title=Official Languages Ordinance, Official languages and their status and use (Cap 5, Section 3)|accessdate=17 July 2013|work=[[Department of Justice (Hong Kong)|HKSAR Department of Justice]]}}</ref> It dictates that all ordinances would be enacted and published in both languages,<ref name="cap5_sec4">{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.hk/blis_ind.nsf/CurAllEngDoc/14D3D4F60818B3CBC825648000408D52?OpenDocument|title=Official Languages Ordinance, Enactment of Ordinances in both official languages (Cap 5, Section 4)|accessdate=17 July 2013|work=HKSAR Department of Justice}}</ref> and allows judicial officers the choice of using either language in court proceedings.<ref name="cap5_sec5">{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.hk/blis_ind.nsf/CurAllEngDoc/359730508A4DA498C825648000408D56?OpenDocument|title=Official Languages Ordinance, Judicial proceedings (Cap 5, Section 5)|accessdate=17 July 2013|work=HKSAR Department of Justice}}</ref>
==History== While no law existed prior to 1974 to designate official languages in Hong Kong, by practice, English was the sole language used in all branches of the British colonial government. Under public pressure, the Official Languages Ordinance was enacted in 1974 to declare that both English and Chinese may be used in communication between the government and the public. Despite the usage of different dialects in spoken Chinese, the government chose not to specify a dialect as an official language, instead indicating "Chinese" as an official language, allowing any dialect to be used. Since most of the local population spoke [[Cantonese]], it became the most frequently used dialect in official communication.<ref name="dickson-cumming">{{cite web|publisher=[[National Foundation for Educational Research]]|title=National Profiles of Language Education in 25 Countries|url=http://www.cbs.polyu.edu.hk/ctdso/paper/lang%20in%20ed%20hk%20.pdf|page=41|author=Peter Dickson and [[Alister Cumming]]|publication-date=1996|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>
